1 STATE OF OKLAHOMA
2 2nd Session of the 60th Legislature (2026)
3 COMMITTEE SUBSTITUTE
FOR
4 SENATE BILL 259 By: Howard of the Senate
5 and
6 Newton of the House
7
8
9 COMMITTEE SUBSTITUTE
10 An Act relating to water and water rights; amending
82 O.S. 2021, Sections 1020.12, 1020.15, and 1020.19,
11 which relate to groundwater use, reporting, metering,
and permitting; modifying reporting requirements for
12 certain water use; providing for fines and penalties;
modifying permitting exclusions; requiring Oklahoma
13 Water Resources Board to investigate certain usage
complaints; directing metering and measurement of
14 certain groundwater usage subject to Oklahoma Water
Resources Board monitoring; directing implementation
15 of metering schedule and phase-in; requiring Oklahoma
Water Resources Board to implement certain priorities
16 relating to groundwater use; requiring Oklahoma Water
Resources Board to promulgate rules; amending 82 O.S.
17 2021, Section 1085.2, as last amended by Section 3,
Chapter 164, O.S.L. 2023 (82 O.S. Supp. 2025, Section
18 1085.2), which relates to duties of the Oklahoma
Water Resources Board; expanding duties of the
19 Oklahoma Water Resources Board; updating statutory
language and references; providing for codification;
20 and providing an effective date.
21
22 BE IT ENACTED BY THE PEOPLE OF THE STATE OF OKLAHOMA:
23 SECTION 1. AMENDATORY 82 O.S. 2021, Section 1020.12, is
24 amended to read as follows:
Req. No. 3767 Page 1

1 Section 1020.12. A. Holders of permits shall be required to
2 report to the Oklahoma Water Resources Board annually their use of
3 water pursuant to their permits. Holders of permits shall remit the
4 report as required by the Board in the period following the
5 permitted use. Willful failure to report annual usage may result in
6 cancellation penalties, fines, or suspension of the permit by the
7 Board upon proper notice and hearing as provided in the
8 Administrative Procedures Act. Nonuse, conservation, or usage
9 practices that result in less usage than the permit maximum shall
10 not result in diminishment of the permit holder’s future permitted
11 equal proportional share.
12 B. Holders of permits which use groundwater in connection with
13 an animal feeding operation which houses swine and primarily uses a
14 liquid waste management system where animals are primarily housed in
15 a roof-covered structure shall be required to indicate such use in
16 their annual water use report. Such holders shall also indicate
17 whether or not the animal feeding operation is licensed pursuant to
18 the Oklahoma Concentrated Animal Feeding Operations Act.
19 C. The Board shall notify the State Oklahoma Department of
20 Agriculture, Food, and Forestry of the names and addresses of all
21 permit holders who report usage of groundwater in connection with an
22 animal feeding operation which houses swine and which primarily uses
23 a liquid waste management system where animals are primarily housed
24
Req. No. 3767 Page 2

1 in a roof-covered structure and who are not licensed pursuant to the
2 Oklahoma Concentrated Animal Feeding Operations Act.
3 SECTION 2. AMENDATORY 82 O.S. 2021, Section 1020.15, is
4 amended to read as follows:
5 Section 1020.15. A. The Oklahoma Water Resources Board shall
6 not permit any groundwater user to commit waste by:
7 1. Drilling a well, taking, or using groundwater without a
8 permit, except for domestic use as defined in this title;
9 2. Taking more groundwater than is authorized by the permit;
10 3. Taking or using groundwater in any manner so that the water
11 is lost for beneficial use;
12 4. Transporting groundwater from a well to the place of use in
13 such a manner that there is an excessive loss in transit;
14 5. Using groundwater in such an inefficient manner that
15 excessive losses occur;
16 6. Allowing any groundwater to reach a pervious stratum and be
17 lost into cavernous or otherwise pervious materials encountered in a
18 well;
19 7. Permitting or causing the pollution of a fresh water strata
20 or basin through any act which will permit fresh groundwater
21 polluted by minerals or other waste to filter or otherwise intrude
22 into such a basin or subbasin. The Board shall be precluded from
23 determining whether waste by pollution will occur pursuant to the
24 provisions of this paragraph if the activity for which the applicant
Req. No. 3767 Page 3

1 or w ater user intends to or has used the water as specified under
2 Section 1020.9 of this title is required to comply with rules and
3 requirements of or is within the jurisdictional areas of
4 environmental responsibility of the Department of Environmental
5 Quality or the Oklahoma Department of Agriculture, Food, and
6 Forestry;
7 8. Drilling wells and producing groundwater therefrom except in
8 accordance with the well spacing previously determined by the Board;
9 9. Using groundwater for air conditioning or cooling purposes
10 without providing facilities to aerate and reuse such water; or
11 10. Failure Failing to properly plug abandoned water wells in
12 accordance with rules of the Board and file reports thereof.
13 B. Complaints by any individual in violation of the provisions
14 of subsection A of this section shall be made to the Board and to
15 the local groundwater irrigation district, if such district is
16 established pursuant to the Groundwater Irrigation District Act.
17 Investigation of such complaints shall be made by the Board, in
18 conjunction with such other agencies, boards, or the district, with
19 which the Board may contract. Except as otherwise provided by
20 paragraph 7 of subsection A of this section, any employee of the
21 Board having evidence that an act of waste is being committed in his
22 or her presence, or after investigation of a complaint filed by
23 another individual, shall take steps to assure that the waste ceases
24 upon review of reporting, audits of usage, an investigation of a
Req. No. 3767 Page 4

1 comp laint filed by any person, or the Board’s own independent
2 determination, the Board shall take action to cease commission of
3 such waste and impose fines and penalties on such user as provided
4 in Section 1020.22 of this title. Such steps shall include, but
5 shall not be limited to pursuing voluntary compliance, obtaining the
6 issuance of a cease and desist order by the Executive Director of
7 the Oklahoma Water Resources Board, imposing progressive fines and
8 penalties related to the severity and frequency of waste, requiring
9 more frequent reporting of usage, instituting action in a court of
10 competent jurisdiction to enjoin the waste, pursuing a suspension of
11 any suspending the permit or other administrative remedies by the
12 Board, and filing a complaint in the district court of the county
13 wherein such violation has occurred, and it shall be the duty of the
14 district attorney of said such county to prosecute such complaint.
15 C. In cases of waste by pollution pursuant to paragraph 7 of
16 subsection A of this section, any complaint or investigation, or any
17 enforcement matter other than an individual proceeding involving the
18 suspension of an Oklahoma Water Resources Board permit, shall be
19 referred to and subject to the jurisdiction of the Department of
20 Environmental Quality or other appropriate state environmental
21 agency or state agency with limited environmental responsibility.
22 SECTION 3. AMENDATORY 82 O.S. 2021, Section 1020.19, is
23 amended to read as follows:
24
Req. No. 3767 Page 5

1 Section 1020.19. Upon request of a majority of the landowners
2 residing within a basin or subbasin, the Board is authorized to
3 require that water wells be metered and that such meters as the
4 Board shall approve be utilized by the applicant and placed under
5 seal, subject to reading by the agents of the Board at any time.
6 A. The Oklahoma Water Resources Board may also shall require
7 that the applicant report the reading of such meters at reasonable
8 intervals all water wells requiring a permit to take and use
9 groundwater from the Oklahoma Water Resources Board be equipped at
10 any central point of distribution with water well flow meters or an
11 alternative measuring system as defined by the Board. The water
12 well flow meter or alternative measuring system shall have
13 contemporary, verifiable records, as defined by the Board. The
14 meter or alternative measuring system shall remain on the point of
15 distribution and in proper operating condition at all times when
16 groundwater is being produced. Data from the meter or alternative
17 measuring system shall be reported to the Board annually. Data from
18 the meter or alternative measuring system shall be utilized for the
19 annual groundwater use report. The meter and measurement
20 requirements of this section shall be implemented pursuant to the
21 provisions of Section 4 of this act.
22 B. Beginning January 1, 2027, a five-year allocation of the
23 maximum annual yield of the basin or subbasin may be approved for a
24 regular permit. An applicant for a five-year allocation shall be
Req. No. 3767 Page 6

1 requ ired to submit annual usage as determined by a water well flow
2 meter or highly accurate alternative measuring device approved by
3 the Board and pay the annual permit fee. If approved by the Board,
4 the applicant may exceed the maximum annual yield in any year of the
5 five-year allocation by an amount as set by the Board, not to exceed
6 one hundred fifty percent (150%) of the amount of any single-year
7 maximum of the permit; provided, the applicant shall adhere to the
8 cumulative permit maximum over the five-year period.
9 C. Except as otherwise provided in this act, the Oklahoma Water
10 Resources Board shall promulgate any rules necessary to implement
11 the provisions of this section.
12 SECTION 4. NEW LAW A new section of law to be codified
13 in the Oklahoma Statutes as Section 1020.19A of Title 82, unless
14 there is created a duplication in numbering, reads as follows:
15 A. The Oklahoma Water Resources Board shall promulgate rules to
16 establish a phase-in schedule and plan for the meter and measurement
17 requirements established in Section 1020.19 of Title 82 of the
18 Oklahoma Statutes to ensure that the requirements are implemented
19 statewide not later than eight (8) years following the effective
20 date of this act.
21 B. The Board is authorized to promulgate rules and procedures
22 regarding the spacing of wells within groundwater basins. The
23 determinations made on the spacing of wells within a basin shall be
24 specific to that basin.
Req. No. 3767 Page 7

1 SECTION 5. NEW LAW A new section of law to be codified
2 in the Oklahoma Statutes as Section 1020.19B of Title 82, unless
3 there is created a duplication in numbering, reads as follows:
4 The Oklahoma Water Resources Board shall promulgate rules and
5 implement policies for the purposes of directing its agents,
6 employees, and systems to:
7 1. Accept, audit, and review reporting on a timely basis from
8 permitted groundwater users;
9 2. Modernize its data collection system with respect to
10 permitted groundwater users and implement a program to receive and
11 index usage reports by an online or electronic system;
12 3. Investigate any claims of waste pursuant to Section 1020.15
13 of Title 82 of the Oklahoma Statutes; and
14 4. Impose fines and penalties for overuse of water allotments
15 under a permit by any permitted well user or waste pursuant to
16 Section 1020.15 of Title 82 of the Oklahoma Statutes.
17 SECTION 6. AMENDATORY 82 O.S. 2021, Section 1085.2, as
18 last amended by Section 3, Chapter 164, O.S.L. 2023 (82 O.S. Supp.
19 2025, Section 1085.2), is amended to read as follows:
20 Section 1085.2. In addition to any and all other authority
21 conferred upon it by law, the Oklahoma Water Resources Board shall
22 also have authority:
23 1. Generally to do all such things as in its judgment may be
24 necessary, proper, or expedient in the accomplishment of its duties;
Req. No. 3767 Page 8

1 2. To make such contracts and execute such instruments as in
2 the judgment of the Board are necessary or convenient to the
3 exercise of any of the powers conferred upon it by law. Provided,
4 however, no contract shall be made conveying the title or use of any
5 waters of the State of Oklahoma this state to any person, firm,
6 corporation, or other state or subdivision of government, for sale
7 or use in any other state, unless such contract be is specifically
8 authorized by an act of the Oklahoma Legislature and thereafter as
9 approved by it;
10 3. To negotiate contracts and other agreements with the federal
11 government to arrange for the development of water resources and for
12 the storage and distribution of water for beneficial purposes;
13 provided, however, that the Board shall act in such capacity only as
14 an intermediary in assisting others, and under no circumstances
15 shall the Board have any power or authority to build, construct, or
16 finance any waterways, dams, or other such projects for itself,
17 except as may be otherwise specifically provided by the laws of this
18 state;
19 4. To develop statewide and local plans to assure the best and
20 most effective use and control of water to meet both the current and
21 long-range needs of the people of Oklahoma this state; to cooperate
22 in such planning with any public or private agency, entity, or
23 person interested in water, and is directed to prepare such plans
24 for consideration and approval by the Legislature; and to aid, at
Req. No. 3767 Page 9

1 all times, counties, incorporated cities and towns, and special
2 purpose districts in the state in promoting and developing flood
3 control and water conservation in the state;
4 5. To employ and fix the compensation of such officers, agents,
5 attorneys, technical personnel, and employees of the Board as it
6 shall deem necessary to the proper performance of its duties;
7 6. To adopt and use an official seal;
8 7. To promulgate such rules and make orders as it may deem
9 necessary or convenient to the exercise of any of the powers or the
10 performance of any of the duties conferred or imposed upon it by
11 this or any other law;
12 8. To institute and maintain, or to intervene in, any actions
13 or proceedings in or before any court, board, commission, or officer
14 of this or any other state or of the United States to stop or
15 prevent any use, misuse, appropriation, or taking of any of the
16 waters of this state which is in whole or in part in violation of
17 any law, or of any rules, orders, judgments, or decrees of any
18 court, board, commission, or officer of this or any state or of the
19 United States; and to institute and maintain or intervene in any
20 other action or proceeding where the Board deems it necessary to the
21 proper execution and discharge of any of the powers or duties
22 conferred or imposed upon it by law;
23
24
Req. No. 3767 Page 10

1 9. To determine, charge, and receive fees to be collected in
2 advance for the filing and examination of applications for permits
3 to:
4 a. construct water use works,
5 b. appropriate groundwater,
6 c. appropriate stream water,
7 d. establish vested rights,
8 e. inspect water use works,
9 f. file other papers,
10 g. make copies of documents,
11 h. make prints of maps and drawings,
12 i. certify copies of documents, maps, and drawings,
13 j. file transfers of water rights,
14 k. gauge wells and ditches, changes in point of
15 diversion, and changes in place of use of water,
16 l. test wells, and
17 m. hold hearings, make records, and provide transcripts
18 of hearings.
19 Such fees shall not be collected from any state agency or state
20 institution;
21 10. To negotiate contracts or water compacts with the federal
22 government or any department or bureau thereof, or with any other
23 state for the purpose of obtaining assistance and cooperation in the
24 accomplishment of the purpose of flood control and water
Req. No. 3767 Page 11

1 cons ervation and use in the state. To that end, the Board may match
2 funds with the federal government and with other states upon such
3 terms as shall be agreed upon and approved by the Governor of the
4 state, with the limitation that contracts or water compacts with
5 other states for the division and apportionment of the cost and use
6 of the water controlled by interstate projects shall be submitted to
7 and approved by the Legislature of the state and the Governor of the
8 state, and Congress and the President of the United States
9 conformable to the State Oklahoma Constitution and Federal
10 Constitutions the United States Constitution;
11 11. To accept gifts and grants of money and property or any
12 interest therein;
13 12. To provide funding from federal and state monies for water
14 and wastewater project purposes to eligible entities for preliminary
15 engineering reports and planning and feasibility studies;
16 13. To sell or dispose of real or personal property held by the
17 Board when no longer needed in such manner as provided by law;
18 14. To make appropriations of water to all special purpose
19 districts;
20 15. To execute and deliver, without actual consideration
21 therefor, a written release of any easement or easement deed
22 heretofore given to the Oklahoma Conservation Commission of the
23 State of Oklahoma, the Planning and Resources Board or the Oklahoma
24 Water Resources Board on lands situated in this state, whenever it
Req. No. 3767 Page 12

1 shal l appear to said the Oklahoma Water Resources Board that the
2 need for such easement or easement deed no longer exists; provided,
3 the owner of the lands affected shall file a written application for
4 such release with the Oklahoma Water Resources Board;
5 16. To review disputes involving service areas or territories,
6 rates for raw or treated water, and abrogation clauses in contracts
7 among municipalities and rural water districts or not-for-profit
8 rural water corporations; to recommend mediation and refer parties
9 in appropriate disputes to mediators and provide technical
10 information to such mediators; and to recommend other means of
11 resolving disputes; provided, that no party to such dispute may
12 initiate action in any district court regarding the dispute until
13 written notice of the dispute has been filed with the Board;
14 provided further, that the provisions of this paragraph shall not be
15 construed to diminish any right of access to the court granted to a
16 party by law;
17 17. To provide workshop training sessions for board members of
18 rural water districts and not-for-profit rural water corporations
19 throughout the year on a regional basis for the purpose of study and
20 instruction in the areas of financing, law, and the ethics, duties,
21 and responsibilities of such board members. Such training shall be
22 provided by the Board in conjunction with the Oklahoma Rural Water
23 Association as required by law. To the extent possible, the Board
24 shall attempt to schedule training workshops in three-hour segments
Req. No. 3767 Page 13

1 to b e held in any public facility at a time convenient to the
2 attendees;
3 18. To establish an agency special account through the Office
4 of Management and Enterprise Services and the State Treasurer’s
5 Office of the State Treasurer as necessary for the collection and
6 distribution of funds, including funds of sponsors and registration
7 fees related to conferences, meetings, and training sessions; and
8 19. To accredit persons having requisite knowledge in
9 floodplain management and in minimization and prevention of flood
10 hazards and losses; and
11 20. To impose fines and penalties for overuse of water
12 allotments by any permitted well user or any unpermitted well user
13 who is not a domestic user pursuant to this title. Such fines and
14 penalties shall be progressive in nature related to severity and
15 frequency of overuse or unpermitted use and shall result in
16 suspension of a permit upon findings of willful disregard of
17 requirements by the user or multiple infractions by any permitted
18 user over the entirety of the user’s permits.
19 SECTION 7. This act shall become effective November 1, 2026.
